 <entry gd:kind="buzz#person">
  <id>114642890281206187312</id>
  <displayName>Kurt von Schleicher</displayName>
  <aboutMe>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I’m one grateful, very contented ordinary-Joe that’s been forgiven and now is trying to help my friends. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Did you know that according to one survey, 76% of Americans believe that they have kept the first Commandment. Incredible huh, because who could muster that kind of discipline in our world and actually pull that off? Only One has. Sinless Jesus did, but I couldn’t and haven’t. That&amp;#39;s why I needed and still need Him. &lt;span&gt;   &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;My California pastor once told me about some seminarians who were asked to properly situate God’s so called Top Ten List—the Ten Commandments in their best order according to their importance and how they thought they should be ordered.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Those Bible students did feel that the sixth commandment—&amp;quot;You shall not murder&amp;quot;—should be in the nummero uno slot, and that the seventh commandment—&amp;quot;You shall not commit adultery&amp;quot;—should also be right up there close under number six.&lt;span&gt;  &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Where did they want to put the first commandment—&amp;quot;You shall have no other gods before Me&amp;quot;? They decided that it should be at the bottom of their list. They didn&amp;#39;t feel that it was all that important really. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;But God listed it, however, at the top of em all for a very good reason. He knew that if you or I blow it with the Father’s number one commandment, then everything else will fall apart for us. Have you given preeminence to anything other than the Lord in your life? What do you talk about and think about the most. Even good things can become bad for us if we put them first--that&amp;#39;s what idolatry is all about ..even in our day. &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;I love how Jesus said, &amp;quot;The most important commandment is this: `Hear, O Israel! The Lord our God is the one and only Lord. And you must love the Lord your God with all your heart, all your soul, all your mind, and all your strength.&amp;#39; The second is equally important: `Love your neighbor as yourself.&amp;#39; No other commandment is greater than these&amp;quot; “Mk. 12:29-31, nlt).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;Have things fallen apart in you life.. or do ya still need forgiveness? Have you really kept God&amp;#39;s Top Ten List? You can have forgiveness in Jesus Christ right now. Why wait? See...&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

 <entry gd:kind="buzz#person">
  <id>112058474141856164031</id>
  <displayName>Wade Roush</displayName>
  <aboutMe>&lt;p&gt;Wade Roush is Chief Correspondent for Xconomy. He is a veteran science and
technology writer whose recent work has focused on startups and innovation, consumer Internet
technology, social computing, geocomputing, virtual worlds, and the visual Web. He lives in Boston with his Australian Shepherd dog, Rhody, and blogs informally at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.travelswithrhody.net&quot;&gt;Travels with Rhody&lt;/a&gt;. He is the author of &lt;a style=&quot;font-style:italic&quot; href=&quot;http://www.amazon.com/Pixel-Nation-Weeks-World-ebook/dp/B0037263MM/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;amp;m=AG56TWVU5XWC2&amp;amp;s=digital-text&amp;amp;qid=1266094988&amp;amp;sr=1-1&quot;&gt;Pixel Nation&lt;/a&gt;, a collection of his online technology columns for Xconomy.&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
As a staff member at MIT’s &lt;em&gt;Technology Review&lt;/em&gt; from 2001
to 2006, Roush served as senior editor, San Francisco bureau chief, and
executive editor of TechnologyReview.com, and helped lead the magazine
to a nomination as National Magazine Award finalist in 2006. Before
joining &lt;em&gt;TR&lt;/em&gt;, he was the Boston bureau reporter for &lt;em&gt;Science&lt;/em&gt;, managing editor of supercomputing publications at NASA Ames Research Center, and Web editor at e-book pioneer Nuvomedia.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Roush graduated Magna cum Laude in the history of science from
Harvard College in 1989 and earned a PhD in the history and social
study of science and technology from MIT in 1994. His work has appeared
in &lt;em&gt;Science&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Technology Review&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;IEEE Spectrum&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Encyclopaedia Brittanica&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Technology and Culture&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;Alaska Airlines Magazine&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;World Business&lt;/em&gt;, and he has been a guest of CNN, CNBC, NECN, WGBH and NPR.</aboutMe>
  <profileUrl>http://www.google.com/profiles/wade.roush</profileUrl>
